reviews.review_text:
Thanks! Hey Folks - 
Thanks for posting this recording and reuniting me with the Master Cassette soundboards that I lost during college. Great show along with some sentimental value as well, I suppose.
I, along with a few friends, was a guest of the band that night and, at the end of the night, Dan Healy popped the cassettes out of the soundboard and gave them to us - Maxell XLIIS's, if I remember correctly. 
I held on to those tapes for a few years but then lost them in college ~1989 - always knew they would show up again somehow.... thanks!

The First Of What Would Be Many!!!! This was the show that triggered 3 years of non-stop touring for me. Everyone's got a 1st show and this was mine. I would never be the same!

A solid 85' performance with that Killer 85' Healy sound. Most notable is the steller Scarlet->Fire segway and the rare "Walking The Dog."

I lost my Maxell XLII's copy years ago too so thanks for posting it here for us to download.

Cheers All,

Shakedave
Colorado

You know this space is getting hot Ok, Ok, I know that I hand out far too many 5 stars to 1985 shows, but this one is so very tight. Despite a rather "predicatable" second set, this show really is very strong start to finish both in terms of the recording and the playing. Weir is LOUD here and seems to be having a very good time at that. Jerry flubs lyrics in Althea, but it's really pretty minor, and as with all 1985 Althea's (too rare: only 9!) it is just packed sick Jerry leads.

Strong performance 4 out of 5.

Good energy from the band

Smoking! I wish I had a copy. My 3rd or 4th show. Ah sweet highschool memories.  Could anyone send me a copy of this board?  I'm a bit inept technologically but Im trying to learn.  I know it's late to be trying to download these boards... can anyone help a brother out.  Any advice at all.  thanks
billy_bob_burke@yahoo.com

Hey Now! Good show! I typically don't like the mid-80s, but was suggested to listen to this show. I expected the worst, but ended up with a pretty good show. The first set SMOKES from beginning to end with a Bird Song and LLR that really hooked me. The second set, while being a bit predictable, is still solid, at least until drums>space. Great versions of Scarlet>Fire and Estimated>Eyes. It does tail off a bit at the end, but still holds up pretty well. 

Sound is superb, show is great (minus the second half of the second set), so I'd give it 4.5 stars if I could...but seeing as this is one of the best shows I've heard from the mid-80s, I'll give it a hesitant 5.

GD live Medowlands Aug. '85 - 11 - 11 All '85 shows were OUTSTANDING and all shows on East Coast WOWED the pants off folk. Maine, RI......AND the JGB FORKIN' ROCKED OUT, '91 - '94 for me + '85 - '90. Gee, I guess that sums it up.  East Coast shows blew up!

35 years ago tonight ... Listening to this show exactly 35 years later brings back the memories. Like so many, I discovered The Dead in college - thanks Mags! As a big fan of Scarlet / Fire, I was psyched to catch the only S/F of the '85 east coast fall tour. This was my sixth show, after 4/4/85, 6/27/85, 11/4/85, 11/5/85, and 11/8/85. Didn't see S/F again until SPAC '88. Still can't believe I Hitchhiked from Boston to The Meadowlands and made it in time for the show. The Gods smiled on me, and 11/11 has been my favorite holiday ever since. Overall a great show with a solid song selection and lively jamming. I particularly enjoyed Birdsong, LLR, and Mr. Fantasy. Brokedown ending the tour was poignant in '85, and brings a tear to my eye on 11/11/20.

This show was a magic experience for me, and I'll always think fondly of it, especially in light of what was to come. '86-88 would be tough years for the band, for the fans, and for me personally. Things turned around in '89 when I landed a dream job and the band got their groove back. But, due to said job, I missed some of the best shows from Fall '89 (10/16/89) and  Spring '90 (3/29/90). I caught the whole run in my hometown during the glorious Boston Garden shows of '91, maybe their last great year. 

Of course, every show was a gift, and I felt especially blessed to have been in New Jersey on 11/11/85. Shout out to all my "concert brothers" who were also in attendance. I picked up a grey baseball style shirt that night, now long gone, that depicted the band as characters from Alice in Wonderland, captioned "Grateful Dead - It's Worth The Trip."

Indeed.
